title.narrative: PUBLIC HEALTH EMERGENCY

description.narrative: By 2025, children and their families access timely and quality health services in humanitarian situations through improved national and subnational capacities in responding to public health emergencies., which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2025, more neonates, infants and children survive and thrive, and fewer women die during pregnancy and childbirth.

title.narrative: By 2025, children and their families access timely and quality health services in humanitarian situations through improved nationaland subnational capacities in responding to public health emergencies.

description.narrative: Despite the triple threats of floods, locusts, and COVID-19, UNICEF Somalia made good progress in improving access to lifesaving emergency healthcare services. By the end of December, 443,166 people, including 214,779;children under-five, have been provided with essential and lifesaving healthcare in areas of highest needs and lowest level of access. These results were achieved in the context of drought, displacements, disease outbreaks and inequities, and they will contribute to a further reduction of U5 child mortality rates. | Status:Partially met | As-of Date:17/12/2021
